Building a Basic Data Analysis Workflow in R

Ill be covering the basic tasks needed to conduct common analyses. I think people are intimidated by R because they dont know how to start. So, Ill begin by covering things like importing data (using code and RStudio tools), recoding variables, working with subsets of data, and running descriptive statistics. Then some basic exploratory plots, correlations, regression, and ANOVA. After weve covered that basic ground I can take questions and/or cover some more advanced tasks.

Anyone else feeling like

We can combine all of these operations with the pipe operator!

%>% automatically supplies the output from the previous step as the first argument to the next function. select(), mutate(), and arrange() are all designed to work with the pipe operator, so they take the data as the first argument.

The pipe operator is great, because it improves readability, and lets you write the operations in the order in which they happen.

stanton_homeruns %>% 
    
    select(game_date,
           pitch_type,
           launch_speed,
           hit_distance) %>% 
    
    mutate(launch_speed = as.numeric(launch_speed),
           hit_distance = as.numeric(hit_distance)) %>%
    
    arrange(desc(launch_speed)) %>% 
    
    print()
## # A tibble: 267 x 4
##    game_date pitch_type launch_speed hit_distance
##    <chr>     <chr>             <dbl>        <dbl>
##  1 6/23/2015 CU                 119.         479.
##  2 9/28/2017 SL                 119.         467.
##  3 4/23/2015 FF                 118.         377.
##  4 8/25/2017 FT                 118.         462.
##  5 4/30/2016 CH                 117.         462.
##  6 9/23/2017 CU                 117.         419.
##  7 9/20/2017 CU                 117.         399.
##  8 8/6/2016  CH                 116.         504.
##  9 7/23/2016 CU                 116.         441.
## 10 8/24/2017 FF                 116.         424.
## # ... with 257 more rows

(In RStudio, you can use the keyboard shortcuts Ctrl + Shift + M on Windows or Cmd + Shift + M on Mac. You can also hit Alt/Option+Shift+K to check out RStudios keyboard shortcuts.)

You can use . as a stand-in for the data, to get a better sense of whats going on here:

stanton_homeruns %>% 
    
    select(.data = .,
           game_date,
           pitch_type,
           launch_speed,
           hit_distance) %>% 
    
    mutate(.data = .,
           launch_speed = as.numeric(launch_speed),
           hit_distance = as.numeric(hit_distance)) %>% 
    
    arrange(.data = ., 
            desc(launch_speed)) %>% 
    
    print()

Working with a subset of data

Lets look only at Stantons home runs > 100 mph.

First lets create a new dataset from the code above:

## Remove the other intermediate datasets from before ##

rm(stanton_homeruns_1, stanton_homeruns_2, stanton_homeruns_3)

## Now call this new dataset "stanton_homeruns_2"

stanton_homeruns_2 <- 
    
    stanton_homeruns %>% 
    
    select(game_date,
           pitch_type,
           launch_speed,
           hit_distance) %>% 
    
    mutate(launch_speed = as.numeric(launch_speed),
           hit_distance = as.numeric(hit_distance)) %>% 
    
    arrange(desc(launch_speed))

We create a subset simply by adding a filter() operation:

stanton_homeruns_2 %>% filter(launch_speed > 100)

103 of his 267 home runs have been > 100 mph.

Lets take a look at some descriptive statistics

install.packages("psych")       # Will install the default location

We can also summarize just the 2 numeric variables using dplyr::summarize_at(), which is a scoped version of dplyr::summarize().

stanton_homeruns_2 %>% 
    summarize_at(
        .vars = vars(launch_speed, hit_distance), 
        .funs = funs(mean(., na.rm = TRUE), sd(., na.rm = TRUE)))

Exploratory plots

Whats the association between speed and distance?

We can create beautiful plots using the ggplot2 package.

Theres literally an entire book on ggplot2, so theres a lot you can do. Ill just specify a plot that I like.

Lets make a scatterplot with a linear best fit line.

stanton_plot_1 <- 
    stanton_homeruns_2 %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = launch_speed, y = hit_distance)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
    labs(title = "Giancarlo Stanton home runs: Speed vs. distance",
         x = "Launch speed",
         y = "Hit distance",
         subtitle = "Not surprising!") +
    theme_bw()

stanton_plot_1

Saving a plot

Lets save that to the plots folder

ggsave(plot = stanton_plot_1, filename = "plots/stanton_plot_1.png")

Analyses

Corelation

Lets look at the correlation of speed and distance

First lets load the broom package:

library(broom)

This standardizes R model output. Ill show you the difference.

First the correlation test:

stanton_cor <-
    with(stanton_homeruns_2, 
         cor.test(x = launch_speed, y = hit_distance))

Now the output using print()

print(stanton_cor)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation

tidy(stanton_cor)

Regression

Lets run a regression, then get output for the terms, and model statistics

stanton_fit_1 <- lm(hit_distance ~ launch_speed, data = stanton_homeruns_2)

## Terms ##

tidy(stanton_fit_1)
## Statistics ##

glance(stanton_fit_1)

Lets add pitch type as a categorical predictor

stanton_fit_2 <- lm(hit_distance ~ launch_speed + pitch_type, data = stanton_homeruns_2)

## Terms ##

tidy(stanton_fit_2)
## Statistics ##

glance(stanton_fit_2)
